snippet.textDisplay:
"...political, social and economic upheaval...." - just look at Ireland. Highly unusual, historic, significant and sudden shift in political vote shattering the establishment parties and the status quo. While there are a multitude of variables that likely influenced Ireland, including paramilitary organisation, the DUP's, inclusion in the British government during Brexit negotiations and the eventual exit of Britain from Europe, the consequential upcoming next stage further border and trade negotiations, the passing of the 100 year mark of independence for ROI and so much more; there remains also the fact that border issues with Britain-Europe are a significant factor in Corona virus control concerns, and not just the sovereignty and security of the island Nation (ROI) on the furthest periphery of Europe. A country in which "the border" and it's integrity has been central to everything for over a century and quite intensively during recent Brexit years, it is not impossible that Ireland has already seen some influence of the corona virus threat in its recent elections. And can anyone really say that they are wrong? Given the circumstances.

What if Britain had not enacted a travel ban with China because economy was more important post Brexit than health and "let's not be silly now plebs". What then for the island of Ireland, and Europe? Same applies for agricultural devastation with Foot and Mouth or threats to the food chain with BSE/CJD.
Westminster and DUP would sooner run Northern Irish economy into the ground than grow up and do the sensible thing during their exit agreements - whatever that might going to look like? (The great unknown)
